========

How Data Flows

Context Words
      │
      ▼
One-Hot Encoding
      │
      ▼
Embedding Matrix (W)
      │
      ▼
Average Vectors
      │
      ▼
Hidden Layer
      │
      ▼
Output Weight Matrix (W')
      │
      ▼
Predict Target Word

==================

Components

| Symbol                 | Meaning                                | Simple Explanation                                                                                     |
| ---------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **x₁k, x₂k, ..., xck** | Input Context Words                    | Context words given as input to predict the target word.                                               |
| **Input Layer**        | One-hot encoded context words          | Each context word is converted into a one-hot vector.                                                  |
| **W (V × N)**          | Input Weight Matrix (Embedding Matrix) | Converts one-hot vectors into dense embedding vectors. These are the word embeddings that are learned. |
| **Hidden Layer (h)**   | Average of context embeddings          | CBOW averages all context word vectors into a single vector.                                           |
| **W' (N × V)**         | Output Weight Matrix                   | Maps the hidden vector back to the vocabulary.                                                         |
| **Output Layer (y)**   | Predicted Target Word                  | Produces probabilities for all words and predicts the most likely target word.                         |

=======

Example

Sentence:

The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog

Window Size = 2

Target Word:

fox

Context Words:

quick
brown
jumps
over
Step 1: Input Layer
quick
brown
jumps
over

↓

Step 2: Embedding Matrix (W)

Each word gets an embedding vector.

quick → [0.2, 0.4, 0.6]

brown → [0.3, 0.5, 0.4]

jumps → [0.7, 0.2, 0.5]

over  → [0.4, 0.6, 0.8]

↓

Step 3: Hidden Layer

Average all four vectors.

Average =
([0.2,0.4,0.6] +
 [0.3,0.5,0.4] +
 [0.7,0.2,0.5] +
 [0.4,0.6,0.8]) / 4

=
[0.40, 0.425, 0.575]

↓

Step 4: Output Layer

The hidden vector is compared with every word in the vocabulary.

The      → 0.01

quick    → 0.02

brown    → 0.03

fox      → 0.94  ✅

dog      → 0.01

The highest probability is fox, so the prediction is correct.

=========

Meaning of Symbols


| Symbol | Meaning                                                                     |
| ------ | --------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **V**  | Vocabulary Size (total number of unique words)                              |
| **N**  | Embedding Size (number of dimensions in each word vector, e.g., 100 or 300) |
| **C**  | Number of Context Words (depends on the window size)                        |
| **h**  | Hidden Layer (average context vector)                                       |
| **y**  | Output (predicted target word probabilities)                                |









